00:22:11.466 --> 00:22:15.096
Periodic Table from here to
here?

00:22:15.096 --> 00:22:18.159
It increases.
You are right,

00:22:18.159 --> 00:22:22.016
recitation five.
Here is the trend.

00:22:22.016 --> 00:22:26.554
Here is row one,
from hydrogen to helium.

00:22:26.554 --> 00:22:32.000
Here is row two,
from lithium to neon.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:35.548
It increases.
It increases because,

00:22:35.548 --> 00:22:41.080
as you go across the Periodic
Table here, Z increases.

00:22:41.080 --> 00:22:45.673
The nuclear charge increases.
But, of course,

00:22:45.673 --> 00:22:50.474
there is another parameter
here, and that is r.

00:22:50.474 --> 00:22:55.797
But, as you go across the
Periodic Table right here,

00:22:55.797 --> 00:23:00.494
you are putting electrons into
the same shell,

00:23:00.494 --> 00:23:05.735
essentially.
You are putting those electrons

00:23:05.735 --> 00:23:09.176
into shells that have,
roughly speaking,

00:23:09.176 --> 00:23:12.617
the same distance of r from the
nucleus.

00:23:12.617 --> 00:23:18.176
And so the factor that wins out
is Z, the effective charge here.

00:23:18.176 --> 00:23:23.205
And the ionization energy as
you go across then increases.

00:23:23.205 --> 00:23:27.176
But you also see that there are
some glitches.

00:23:27.176 --> 00:23:33.000
You see that boron is a little
bit lower energy than --

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:42.470
What did I want to say here?
I'm sorry.

00:23:42.470 --> 00:23:46.235
I am looking at it from the
side.

00:23:46.235 --> 00:23:51.764
Here is the electron
configuration of beryllium.

00:23:51.764 --> 00:23:56.000
Here it is, boron,
Z equals 5.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.847
What you see,
here, is that in boron,

00:24:04.847 --> 00:24:09.039
you have to put that extra
electron into the 2p state,

00:24:09.039 --> 00:24:11.491
which requires some more
energy.

00:24:11.491 --> 00:24:16.158
The bottom line is that the
nuclear charge does not increase

00:24:16.158 --> 00:24:20.587
fast enough to compensate
completely for the extra energy

00:24:20.587 --> 00:24:24.146
that you need to have to get to
this 2p state.

00:24:24.146 --> 00:24:28.101
Boron has a little bit lower
ionization energy than

00:24:28.101 --> 00:24:32.728
beryllium.
And to see another glitch,

00:24:32.728 --> 00:24:37.765
that other glitch is between
nitrogen and oxygen.

00:24:37.765 --> 00:24:43.117
Again, we can understand that
glitch by the electron

00:24:43.117 --> 00:24:46.370
configuration.
Here is nitrogen,

00:24:46.370 --> 00:24:49.098
Z equals 7.
Here is oxygen,

00:24:49.098 --> 00:24:53.086
Z equals 8.
And the bottom line here is

00:24:53.086 --> 00:24:57.808
that in oxygen,
you have to put an electron in

00:24:57.808 --> 00:25:04.000
a state in which there already
is an electron.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.623
That is a repulsive
interaction.

00:25:06.623 --> 00:25:11.532
Again, the increase in the
nuclear charge just is not large

00:25:11.532 --> 00:25:16.357
enough to fully compensate for
that repulsive interaction.

00:25:16.357 --> 00:25:21.097
We can understand those little
glitches in terms of these

00:25:21.097 --> 00:25:24.482
electron configurations.
And, in general,

00:25:24.482 --> 00:25:29.476
here, that ionization increases
as we go across the Periodic

00:25:29.476 --> 00:25:32.808
Table.
Here is the third row.

00:25:32.808 --> 00:25:36.753
You also see there are glitches
in the third row.

00:25:36.753 --> 00:25:41.356
You see there is a glitch
between magnesium and aluminum.

00:25:41.356 --> 00:25:45.054
They are right underneath
beryllium and boron.

00:25:45.054 --> 00:25:48.260
A glitch between phosphorous
and sulfur.

00:25:48.260 --> 00:25:51.958
They are right underneath
nitrogen and oxygen.

00:25:51.958 --> 00:25:55.739
For the same reason,
there is a glitch at those

00:25:55.739 --> 00:26:01.000
elements in the second row.
Now, the next question.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:09.232
As we go down a column of the
Periodic Table,

00:26:09.232 --> 00:26:16.154
what happens to the ionization
energy?

00:26:16.154 --> 00:26:18.212
Wait.
Ready?

00:26:18.212 --> 00:26:20.270
Set?
Launch.

00:26:20.270 --> 00:26:26.819
Five.
What happens to the ionization

00:26:26.819 --> 00:26:30.590
energy?
What?

00:26:30.590 --> 00:26:33.425
Decreases.
You are right,

00:26:33.425 --> 00:26:37.795
recitation five.
Why does it decrease?

00:26:37.795 --> 00:26:43.818
It decreases because?
Well, it decreases because you

00:26:43.818 --> 00:26:50.078
are putting electrons into
shells that are farther and

00:26:50.078 --> 00:26:57.283
farther away from the nucleus.
Yes, as you go down the column,

00:26:57.283 --> 00:27:02.870
Z increases.
But it does not increase fast

00:27:02.870 --> 00:27:07.621
enough as r increases.
Remember there are the two

00:27:07.621 --> 00:27:11.382
factors, Z and r.
Although Z increases,

00:27:11.382 --> 00:27:17.023
you are putting the electrons
into shells that are farther

00:27:17.023 --> 00:27:21.279
from the nucleus.
Therefore, that attractive

00:27:21.279 --> 00:27:26.723
interaction does go down,
and the ionization energy goes

00:27:26.723 --> 00:27:29.000
down.
Great.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:33.522
Now, we are going to talk about
another property.

00:27:33.522 --> 00:27:38.328
That other property is called
the electron affinity.

00:27:38.328 --> 00:27:42.191
For example,
if I take chlorine and add an

00:27:42.191 --> 00:27:46.714
electron to it to make chlorine
minus.

00:27:46.714 --> 00:27:51.425
There is an energy change here.
That energy change,

00:27:51.425 --> 00:27:56.136
delta E, is equal to minus 349
kilojoules per mole.

00:27:56.136 --> 00:28:02.868
That is, the fact that this

00:28:02.868 --> 00:28:08.073
energy change is negative,
this tells you that the

00:28:08.073 --> 00:28:13.278
chlorine ion is more stable than
the neutral atom.

00:28:13.278 --> 00:28:19.545
Now, in terms of an equation,
what is the definition here of

00:28:19.545 --> 00:28:24.644
the electron affinity?
That is the next question.

00:28:24.644 --> 00:28:29.000
Are you ready to launch?
Launch.

